{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:46:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:46:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18869"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.53,0.14,0.16,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79891"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11602"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65187"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3949"},{"type":"tags","id":"3981"},{"type":"tags","id":"4558"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79891"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a skiing accident. He sustained a cervical spine injury at the C5 level, confirmed on CT imaging. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears alert but distressed. He has no movement or sensation below the level of his shoulders. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely additional clinical examination finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delayed capillary refill","Bradycardia","Hypothermia","Hypertension","Diaphoresis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a high cervical spinal cord injury (SCI) at C5, which typically results in neurogenic shock due to disruption of sympathetic innervation while parasympathetic function remains intact via the vagus nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBradycardia\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic finding in high cervical spine injuries due to unopposed parasympathetic (vagal) tone. This occurs because the sympathetic outflow from T1-T4 to the heart is disrupted, while the parasympathetic innervation via the vagus nerve remains intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected in acute cervical SCI. Instead, hypotension is typical due to loss of sympathetic tone causing vasodilation. Hypertension may occur later as a complication of autonomic dysreflexia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothermia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in spinal cord injury but is not an immediate finding. The initial temperature is usually normal, though patients may develop poikilothermia (inability to regulate temperature) due to sympathetic disruption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiaphoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically seen in the acute phase of cervical SCI. In fact, patients often have warm, dry skin below the level of injury due to loss of sympathetic innervation to sweat glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed capillary refill\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest poor peripheral perfusion, which while possible due to hypotension, is not a characteristic finding of neurogenic shock where vessels are typically dilated with good peripheral perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical spinal cord injury above T6 can cause neurogenic shock with bradycardia and hypotension due to disruption of sympathetic innervation.","The higher the level of spinal cord injury, the more severe the autonomic dysfunction.","Bradycardia in cervical spine injuries occurs due to unopposed parasympathetic activity via the intact vagus nerve."],"references":["Dave S, Dahlstrom JJ, Weisbrod LJ. Neurogenic Shock. [Updated 2023 Oct 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459361/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65187"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65187"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T10:17:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T10:22:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11602"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79891"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms